docs.abstract: After a legal setback for abortion rights, three Democratic representatives and one Republican shared their personal stories with a House panel.
docs.snippet: After a legal setback for abortion rights, three Democratic representatives and one Republican shared their personal stories with a House panel.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Representative Cori Bush, a Democrat from Missouri, is known on Capitol Hill as a nurse, a pastor, a Black Lives Matter activist and a member of a “squad” of progressive women lawmakers. On Thursday, she told a House panel that she is also a rape survivor who had an abortion after she was attacked on a church trip when she was 17.

headline.main: A Congresswoman’s Story: Raped at 17, ‘I Chose to Have an Abortion’
headline.print_headline: 3 Lawmakers on Capitol Hill Share Accounts of Terminating Their Pregnancies

docs.abstract: Private companies are lagging behind publicly traded firms, but don’t receive the same scrutiny.
docs.snippet: Private companies are lagging behind publicly traded firms, but don’t receive the same scrutiny.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last summer, major public companies across the country pledged to increase diversity in their boardrooms, one of the actions taken after the murder of George Floyd in police custody. Corporate directors set goals, and some have begun to make progress, with investors, activists and others tracking their commitments on racial equity.

headline.main: The Missing Piece in the Push for Boardroom Diversity
headline.print_headline: A Hidden Hurdle in Efforts To Diversify Boardrooms

docs.abstract: Jackie Johnson was indicted by a grand jury in Glynn County, Ga., on charges of “violation of oath of public officer” and “obstruction and hindering a law enforcement officer.”
docs.snippet: Jackie Johnson was indicted by a grand jury in Glynn County, Ga., on charges of “violation of oath of public officer” and “obstruction and hindering a law enforcement officer.”
docs.lead_paragraph: A grand jury indicted a former prosecutor in Georgia on Thursday, accusing her of “showing favor and affection” to one of the men now charged with killing Ahmaud Arbery and for directing police officers not to arrest another suspect.

headline.main: Former Prosecutor in Ahmaud Arbery’s Death Faces Criminal Charges

docs.abstract: Producers say they were led to believe they were making a talk show for A&E, which said no to the program. “You are playing a dangerous game with the truth,” the top producer wrote in his resignation email.
docs.snippet: Producers say they were led to believe they were making a talk show for A&E, which said no to the program. “You are playing a dangerous game with the truth,” the top producer wrote in his resignation email.
docs.lead_paragraph: By the summer of 2020, Brad Bessey was winding down a long career in television, one that included two daytime Emmy Awards and stints as an executive producer at “Entertainment Tonight” and “The Talk.” He was also, like many Americans in the summer of Covid and George Floyd, eager to make a meaningful social contribution. So when his agent approached him about working for a talk show that would go deep on important social questions, and whose host wanted to bring the country together, he jumped at it.

headline.main: Ozy Built a TV Show on a False Claim, Says Its Former Producer
headline.print_headline: Producer Saw Red Flags As Ozy Built A Talk Show

docs.abstract: It’s all about books for Sanyu Dillon, although instead of marketing them, she reads them.
docs.snippet: It’s all about books for Sanyu Dillon, although instead of marketing them, she reads them.
docs.lead_paragraph: “At the beginning of Covid, you could see the evolution of readers’ needs through what was selling,” said Sanyu Dillon, the chief marketing officer for Penguin Random House. It started with a rise in interactive workbooks for children, she said. Later last spring, “baking, cooking, dog training and interior design saw an increase,” she continued. Last summer “was a call for racial justice books after the murder of George Floyd” and last fall, political books were popular.

headline.main: How a Publishing Executive Spends Her Sundays
headline.print_headline: Coffee, Play, Aunties and, of Course, Books

docs.abstract: According to a transcript released Friday, a member of the Minnesota State Patrol said there was “a purge of emails and text messages” after troopers responded to protests in Minneapolis last year.
docs.snippet: According to a transcript released Friday, a member of the Minnesota State Patrol said there was “a purge of emails and text messages” after troopers responded to protests in Minneapolis last year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Minnesota State Patrol troopers deleted text messages and emails shortly after responding to protests that erupted over the police killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis last year, according to a major who testified in federal court in July.

headline.main: Minnesota Troopers Deleted Texts and Emails After Floyd Protests, Major Testifies

docs.abstract: In recent years, a strong interest in books on race and racism has accelerated. Authors, agents and editors are anxious to see how they do.
docs.snippet: In recent years, a strong interest in books on race and racism has accelerated. Authors, agents and editors are anxious to see how they do.
docs.lead_paragraph: After George Floyd was murdered last May, and protests demanding racial justice swelled around the United States, bookstores had trouble keeping “So You Want to Talk About Race” by Ijeoma Oluo in stock. They couldn’t keep “White Fragility” by Robin DiAngelo or “The New Jim Crow,” a 2010 book by Michelle Alexander, on shelves either.

headline.main: Books on Race Filled Best-Seller Lists Last Year. Publishers Took Notice.
headline.print_headline: Books on Race Are Best Sellers, With More Coming

docs.abstract: The decals, with messages such as “Stop Hate” and “Black Lives Matter,” are part of the league’s efforts to show solidarity with players who have protested against racism and police brutality.
docs.snippet: The decals, with messages such as “Stop Hate” and “Black Lives Matter,” are part of the league’s efforts to show solidarity with players who have protested against racism and police brutality.
docs.lead_paragraph: The N.F.L. will allow players to display messages of social justice on their helmets and will stencil the slogans “It Takes All of Us” and “End Racism” on the end zones at every field as part of an effort to show solidarity with the protest movements against racism and police brutality, league officials said.

headline.main: N.F.L. Will Allow Six Social Justice Messages on Players’ Helmets

docs.abstract: Long sidelined, these narratives are ascendant in the culture, and offer an elastic yet demanding view of what it might take for Americans — and their nation — to heal.
docs.snippet: Long sidelined, these narratives are ascendant in the culture, and offer an elastic yet demanding view of what it might take for Americans — and their nation — to heal.
docs.lead_paragraph: FOR ALL THAT was emotionally sobering about the last year, it was literally sobering, too. Many Americans, drinking more than ever during Covid-19 lockdowns and with plenty of time to reflect on it, began to wonder if alcohol was more hindrance than help. The question had been popularized by the sober-curious movement, based on a term coined by the British author Ruby Warrington, and supported by online recovery programs such as Tempest, founded in 2014. But it became especially acute as the incoherent national response to the Covid-19 pandemic conspired with a failing health care system to prove once again that the state could not be trusted to ensure its citizens’ wellness. This was particularly true, the reanimated Black Lives Matter movement announced, when those citizens were brown or Black.

headline.main: The Black Recovery Stories Speaking to Individual and Collective Wellness

byline.original: By Emily Lordi, David Leggett and Shadi Al-Atallah

docs.abstract: Two unanimous rulings allow Gov. Ralph Northam to remove the statue from its prominent spot on Monument Avenue in Richmond.
docs.snippet: Two unanimous rulings allow Gov. Ralph Northam to remove the statue from its prominent spot on Monument Avenue in Richmond.
docs.lead_paragraph: Virginia’s Supreme Court on Thursday unanimously affirmed the power of Gov. Ralph Northam to remove an imposing statue of Robert E. Lee in Richmond, a symbol that had become a target of demonstrators after the death of George Floyd last year.

headline.main: Virginia Supreme Court Clears Path for Removal of Robert E. Lee Statue
